                    <font style="font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(12, 71, 157);"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Featured Article</span></font><br /></td></tr></table><a name="LETTER.BLOCK20" /><table style="display: table;" border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" id="content_LETTER.BLOCK20"><tr><td style="color:#333333;font-family:Trebuchet MS,Verdana,Helvetica,sans-serif;font-size:10pt;" rowspan="1" colspan="1" align="left">

<div align="left"><span style="color:#0c479d;font-family:Trebuchet MS,Verdana,Helvetica,sans-serif;font-size:18pt;"><b> 'Tis the Season For Tantrums</b></span><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,Geneva; font-size: 10pt;"><br /><br />Gearing up for the holidays means getting ready for family, food, presents, excitement and undoubtedly, tantrums.&nbsp; If you find yourself dreading the mood swings that invariably come with the season, it can help to be prepared. Knowing your child's warning signs and having several solutions ready helps prevent meltdowns and keeps your plans running smoothly.<br /><br />Children who are out of their routine tend to get cranky. Consider the many changes that kids experience this time of year. With school on break, eating and sleeping schedules usually change.&nbsp; All the sights and sounds of the holidays can lead children to become overstimulated, and too many sugary treats at home or school are obvious culprits for behavior problems. Large groups, whether at a crowded mall or a family gathering, can overwhelm little ones.&nbsp; Add in travel plans, which bring shortened naptimes, long hours in confined spaces, and late bedtimes in an unfamiliar bed... well, you get the idea. <br /><br />So how is a parent to cope with so many obstacles? Remember that the best way to solve a problem is to first determine the cause. When you have determined what typically triggers your child's tantrums, you can implement specific strategies to prevent them.&nbsp; For example, if lack of food or sleep is an obvious contributing factor, ensuring a nap and a good meal might be all you need.&nbsp; For kids who are bothered by big groups, try leaving them at home with a trusted sitter while you go shopping.&nbsp; When the entire family gets together, set aside a space for your kids to interact with loved ones in a quieter setting. You can also offer incentives for good behavior.&nbsp; Let your child know that if he sits through the huge family dinner without incident, he'll get an extra ten minutes of TV time or an extra book before bed.<br /><br />For those of you who will be driving this holiday season, consider changing your travel routine. Forget rest stops - take exercise breaks! Stop the car, compete to do the most jumping jacks, run to the bathroom, and hop back in the car. We love travel DVD players and Nintendo DS, but when children are quiet and still for a lengthy car ride, their bodies and brains are not being sufficiently stimulated. However, by keeping them active throughout the drive with fun family games, singing, laughter and brief exercise breaks, you just might arrive at grandma's with sleepy and content children.<br /><br />Even when you do your best to prevent them, there will be times when your only option is to stop a tantrum in progress.&nbsp; Creating a diversion, whether by taking the screaming child out the situation or showing them an ornament on the tree, might be all that is needed to calm them down.&nbsp; As frustrating as it can be for parents, some kids just need space or even to be ignored until they have cooled off.&nbsp;&nbsp; Remember that you can't prevent everything, but by planning ahead you can ensure that tantrums don't become the focus of your holiday season.<br /><br /></img></span></div>

<p style="margin: 0in 0in 0.0001pt 0.1732in; color: black; font-style: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 11pt; font-family: Trebuchet MS,Verdana,Helvetica,sans-serif;" align="center"><span style="font-size: 8pt; color: rgb(12, 71, 157);"><a style="color: rgb(12, 71, 157); text-decoration: underline;" href="#Top" shape="rect">Back to Top</a></span><br /></p>
</td></tr></table><a name="LETTER.BLOCK16" /><table style="background-color: rgb(255, 209, 40);" bgcolor="#ffd128" border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" id="content_LETTER.BLOCK16"><tr><td style="color:#333333;font-family:Trebuchet MS,Verdana,Helvetica,sans-serif;font-size:10pt;" rowspan="1" colspan="1" align="left"><span style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(12, 71, 157);">Local Resource</span><br /></td></tr></table><a name="LETTER.BLOCK21" /><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" id="content_LETTER.BLOCK17"><tr><td style="color:#333333;font-family:Trebuchet MS,Verdana,Helvetica,sans-serif;font-size:10pt;" rowspan="1" colspan="1" align="left">
<div align="center"><br /></img></div>
<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Are you new to the area or want to find more information about local businesses?&nbsp; The <a style="color: rgb(12, 71, 157); text-decoration: underline;" track="on" shape="rect" href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?llr=ihw9audab&et=1104021670735&s=-1&e=001KJsctA_g08SwF4rU_0XV--A8qoroVV_Ez1ZHIWNqxAH8BPGA9gONEPuCkTkMj9cBdIittIxuvQ8SGfws99P_0vGRRjT5auT0GZaeUNqtzybyPnxdEs_d0g==" linktype="link" target="_blank">Madison Chamber of Commerce</a> (MCC) is a great resource for information about the community.</span></p>
